Predicting NBA All-Stars for the 2023-2024 Season

Project Members: Anirudha Uppugunduri

This project is independently completed by myself, Anirudha Uppugunduri, and is intended for the usage of CMSC320: Introduction to Data Science of the University of Maryland. All code and prose is written by me. All data sources and resources will be linked down below for reference purposes.

The study is to provide insights into how to predict and visualize similarities between data and statistics from the National Basketball Association. This project is not completely accurate and will not 100% predict the All-Star players for the 2023-2024 NBA Season.

Introduction

The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the highest level of professional basketball in the United States and premier league throughout the entire world. As such, the competition within the NBA is at its peak where players all over the world are paid up to hundreds of millions of dollars to compete. While winning the annual national championship is the highest achievement, there are many other achievements and awards given out throughout every season. These include Most Valuable Player (MVP), Most Improved Player (MIP), Defensive Player of the Year (DPOY), Rookie of the Year (ROY), etc.

The award this study looks to delve into will be the All-Star honors. To describe the All-Star honors, it is recognition given to 12 players for their high-level of play determined by a combination of fan, player, and media voting. The voting procedures are based on the positions that each player plays. Because each position is not the exact same, voting perceptions are a little bit different. For example, taller players generally play the power forward or center position, so they are expected to have more defensive capabilities due to their height as opposed to shorter players who may play the point guard, shooting guard or small forward positions who are expected to score more and have lesser defensive capabilities. However, this is not always the case though as more and more players are changing up their playstyles and are not strictly focused on these criterias which were more enforced in the past (before mid 2010s).

Voting is based on "frontcourt" and "backcourt". The frontcourt consists of three positions: small forward, power forward and center. The backcourt consists of two positions: point guard and shooting guard. Based on how much better they are relative to their peers, these players would end up getting more votes to become All-Stars. These players will then play in the All-Star game during the NBA All-Star weekend. As there are two conferences in the NBA, the eastern and western, there are a total of 24 players chosen as All-Stars. If by any chance they are unable to play in the All-Star weekend due to injury, then a replacement will be selected by the NBA commissioner.

Understanding and discovering patterns to predict future All-Stars for future seasons can lead to many important realizations. Players who are generally All-Stars gain a much more larger following due to their recognition in skill which allow for more traction within their city and eyes to view their games. This brings in more revenue and money for their particular city and allows them to gain a much more stronger basis to qualify for larger contracts as they are more valuable to their particular franchise. To contend for championships, a team must recognize the worth of their players and try to build balanced rosters under the salary cap.

Step 1: Data Collection

As this is the first step of the lifecycle, we need a proper data source to collect information. Basketball-Reference provides a wide variety of statistics and is very trusted as it directly takes stats from the NBA. Since we are visualizing and looking at All-Star statistics, the best dataset of statistics to look at would be player stats from particular NBA seasons. As the game changes very frequently, we'll be using statistics from the past 5 years to act as a baseline.

We'll be using iPython, Jupyter Notebook and the Python programming language as our platforms to collect the information and build visualizations and models to develop the project and understanding. The first thing to do is to import some libraries that we need to use throughout the final tutorial.

    df_dict[key] = pd.DataFrame(player_data)

Step 2: Data Processing

Now that we have all of our data, we can perform some cleaning and remove some of the rows and columns that we do not need. To be more specific, we will remove columns such as Tm, G, MP, FG, FGA, GS, 3P, 3PA, 2P, 2PA, 2P%, FT, FTA, ORB, DRB, TOV and PF. These statistics are highly specific and do not provide as much groundbreaking information when it comes to understanding All-Star statistics. We'll be moreso looking at their offensive and defensive statistics combined to see what their value is as a player. Moreover, because the All-Stars from these years are already determined, we'll create specific dataframes of only All-Stars and check their statistics.

We now need to clean some of the data from the dataframes. There are some empty columns, and some blank indexes we need to fill in with 0 as they are empty strings. There also seems to be multiple rows of the same player show up, which means they have played for multiple teams in the same year as they were traded, so we'll average out and add them as one entry.

In [34]:
dfs = [df2023, df2022, df2021, df2020, df2019]


for i in range(len(dfs)):
    # Drop rows with any NaN values and fill out empty holes
    dfs[i].dropna(how='any', inplace=True)
    dfs[i].replace('', 0.000, inplace=True)

    # Get duplicate players
    counts = dfs[i]['Player'].value_counts()
    duplicate_players = counts[counts > 1].index.tolist()

    # For each duplicate player find all their rows and find the average of their statistics
    for player in duplicate_players:
        player_rows = dfs[i][dfs[i]['Player'] == player]
        player_name = player_rows['Player'].iloc[0]
        player_pos = player_rows['Pos'].iloc[0]

        stats_columns = player_rows.columns.difference(['Player', 'Pos'])
    
        for col in stats_columns:
            player_rows[col] = player_rows[col].astype(float)
            
        averaged_stats = player_rows[stats_columns].mean()
        new_row = pd.DataFrame([{'Player': player_name, 'Pos': player_pos, **averaged_stats.to_dict()}])

        # Dropping rows of the current player
        indices_to_drop = dfs[i][dfs[i]['Player'] == player].index
        dfs[i].drop(indices_to_drop, inplace=True)

        # Adding new row of the current player
        dfs[i] = pd.concat([dfs[i], new_row], ignore_index=True)

df2023, df2022, df2021, df2020, df2019 = dfs

To ensure the data will not get confused by the multiple entries of these players, we will take an average of their current statistics and place them as one entry.

Now, we need to clean the columns for the voting dataframes that we collected earlier. We need to remove some of the columns that were obtained from the parsing procedure and also remove some of the rows which are unnecessary. We also will remove the arbitrary "Score" column which Basketball-Reference uses as it is not entirely clear what the criteria of the Score is though it seems that players with more votes have a lower score.

As per the NBA All-Star voting rules, 50% of weightage is given to the fan votes, 25% to the player votes, and 25% to the media votes. To make this more fair, we'll use the Rank column for each type of category and create a new column called "Vote Score" which defines a singular value for each player. We'll use the formula 0.5(Fan Rank) + 0.25(Player Rank) + 0.25(Media Rank) to define the value of a player's Vote Score.

In [38]:
# Cleaning the dataframes pulled from the voting websites and reorganizing a lot of columns
for key, df in df_dict.items():
    df = df.drop(columns=['header_fans', 'header_players', 'header_media', 'season', 'xyz', 'score'])
    df = df.iloc[2:, 2:]
    df = df.rename(columns={'player_name': 'Player', 'fan_votes': 'Fan Votes', 'fan_rank': 'Fan Rank',
                           'player_votes': 'Player Votes', 'player_rank': 'Player Rank', 'media_votes': 'Media Votes',
                           'media_rank': 'Media Rank'})

    df['Fan Rank'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Fan Rank'], errors='coerce')
    df['Player Rank'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Player Rank'], errors='coerce')
    df['Media Rank'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Media Rank'], errors='coerce')
    df['Vote Score'] = 0.5 * df['Fan Rank'] + 0.25 * df['Player Rank'] + 0.25 * df['Media Rank']
    df_dict[key] = df

# Updating the Vote Score for the entire dataframes for all the players as well which will be helpful
def update_vote_score_in_main_df(main_df, sub_df):
    for _, row in sub_df.iterrows():
        player_name = row['Player']
        vote_score = row['Vote Score']
        if player_name in main_df['Player'].values:
            main_df.loc[main_df['Player'] == player_name, 'Vote Score'] += vote_score
    return main_df

for df in [df2023, df2022, df2021, df2020, df2019]:
    if 'Vote Score' not in df.columns:
        df['Vote Score'] = 0

for name, df in full_df_dict.items():

    elif year == "2022":

    elif year == "2021":
        df2021 = update_vote_score_in_main_df(df2021, df)

Step 3: Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization

Initial Scatterplots

To start off with some initial visualizations, we will measure similiarities between statistics amongst the different players and see if there are any similarities which may tell us some patterns that we can use to determine the criteria to being an All-Star. For example, let's start by creating scatterplots of highest points per game versus vote score. We start off with this as a baseline because scoring is a highly valued statistic and shows direct impact on basketball game.

In [42]:
years = ['2023', '2022', '2021', '2020', '2019']

Based on these initial plots compared to their peers, it's hard to solely conclude that an All-Star is based on one particular skill such as scoring. For example, Jarret Allen barely scored over 16 points as part of the eastern conference frontcourt in 2022, and Draymond Green had not scored even 10 points per game as part of the the western conference frontcourt in 2022. Compared to their peers who had been scoring at a much higher level, these players were still able to power through and gain the All-Star honors. If we look closely at Draymond's statistics though, he averaged 7.3 total rebounds and 7.0 assists. Though he isn't much of a scorer, his passing ability and allowing others to score points as well as securing rebounds to prevent others from scoring or getting second chance opportunity points may have enticed voters to vote for him as they see him as a crucial player contributing to his team's success. Moreover, there are completely arbitrary picks which cannot necessarily be reasoned by statistics alone. For example, the Dirk Nowitizki outlier in the 2019 western conference frontcourt is due to the NBA commissioner granting him All-Star status due to his contributions to the game even though his statistics and Vote Score was abysmal that year. Regardless, it is still in our best interest to be holistic and look at the entirety of a player's capability and not just one specific offensive statistic to determine the All-Star status.

As mentioned before, we now primarily will look at five main categories to describe a player's success when it comes to determining their All-Star success. Because it's hard to determine solely based on one category whether it be offensive or defense, we'll combine all five of these statistics into one new category based on the following formula and logic. In general, the way to win a basketball game is to have a higher score. PTS indicates how many points a player scores, so we'll let the multiplier for that be singular. For every other category, we'll allow the multipler to be by two. AST indicates that a player has assisted another player which accrued points, so it could either range from 2-4 points. For STL, BLK, and TRB, in good faith, we'll assume a steal has converted into at least two points, a block has saved two points, and an offensive rebound leads to at least two points or a defensive rebound saves at least two points. We'll add all these values up and then provide a new categorical score and then compare these values by creating scatterplots once again.

In [43]:
for year, df in combined_dfs.items():
    df['Combined Score'] = df['PTS'] + 2 * (df['AST'] + df['STL'] + df['BLK'] + df['TRB'])

Based on these scatterplots, the All-Star players are more congested on top of each other which we can say that perhaps their combined scores do provide a decent visual measure into telling us whether a larger combined score correlates with All-Star status.

Preliminary Least Squares Model

Instead of solely utilizing scatterplots, let's start with creating a preliminary least squares model. Our model will be used to predict whether there is a linear correlation between one or more independent variables versus our dependent variable. In this case, a player's core five statistics are the independent variables while Vote Score is the dependent variable. Instead of directly using the Combined Score, we want to see how much of an impact each individual statistic of the five have most of an impact, so we'll clearly outline those within our formula. As an initial hypothesis, we predict that there is a linear correlation between these five core statistics and their vote score which translates to having more skill leads to a lower vote score.

In [44]:
results = {}
for year, df in combined_dfs.items():
    temp_df = df.copy() 
    
    X = temp_df[['PTS', 'AST', 'TRB', 'BLK', 'STL']]
    X['AST'] = 2 * X['AST']
    X['TRB'] = 2 * X['TRB']
    X['BLK'] = 2 * X['BLK']
    X['STL'] = 2 * X['STL']
    
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    y = temp_df['Vote Score']
    
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    results[year] = model

for year, result in results.items():
    print(f"Results for {year}:")
    print(result.summary())
    print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

If we take a look at some of the statistics from our OLS Regression models, we can perhaps see some patterns. The important statistics are as following:

  1. coef: the change in the dependent variable for a one-unit change in the predictor variable.
  2. R-Squared: the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables.
  3. P >|t|: the p-value associated with the t-statistic for testing the hypothesis

If we look at the years, it seems that PTS have the lowest p-value which range around 0 in 2023 and 2021, 0.019 in 2022, 0.003 in 2020, and 0.011 in 2019. This is much different compared to the other categories. For example, the p-value for STL is all over the place from being 0.99 in 2023 which we can conclude that players were most likely not chosen as an All-Star for their STL statistic but in 2021 was 0.066 which we could conclude that a player's STL statistic was more effective and impactful.

Moreover, if we look at the coefficients, we can sometimes see smaller negative coefficients for some statistics such as BLK in years such as 2022 and 2021, but they are positive in 2023. The one thing to keep in mind about these coefficients is that PTS is consistently negative, and since the PTS category is a key factor in contributing towards their Combined Score, we can reasonably assume that players who do score a high amount generally have a lower voting score such that they will be more likely to be voted in as an All-Star.

To take a deeper look, we'll create some diagnostic plots which entail plotting residuals vs the fitted values. We'll also make a histogram as well to see how the distribution of residuals looks like. We assume that this distribution should be a normal distribution.

From these diagnostic plots, we can see some further evidence of these players needing athletic performance to boost their status to reach that All-Star level. Most of the residual plots are negatively aligned which is good considering a better vote score is a lower one, and the histogram of residuals seem to be frequently close to 0 which means to say the linear regression model is able to properly map the fitted values.

Now, we're going to use principal component analysis (PCA). Perhaps instead of using our combined score metric to visually explore the impact and use assumptions, we can use PCA to combine all five of the main categories that we want into two principal components which measure the highest variance of the data. PC1 captures the highest variance while PC2 is orthogonal to PC1 which captures the second most variance.

Based on the scatterplots itself, we can see that there are many clustered points within the red box. For example, players like LeBron James and Kevin Durant have been named All-Stars for the past 5 years and have not changed up their playstyle. However, we can also see a few outliers which definitely goes against the grain of the data. When it comes to the variance, about 40% is covered by PC1 and 20% is covered by PC2 which a total of 65% of the variance is covered between both principal components. As the dimensionality of the data has been reduced, 65% is a decent measure, but perhaps more dimensions could have covered more variance as there are many factors into becoming an All-Star.

Model: Analysis, hypothesis testing, & ML

We now create use simple machine learning, more specifically linear regression, to obtain a predictive model to see who the All-Stars are going to be for 2024. This will allow us to predict based on our previous values from the past 5 years and see who is most likely going to be an All-Star. Step 5: Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

This is the step where we understand our data analysis and draw our conclusions regarding whether our predictions will be right for All-Stars. As for now, we can safely say that the logic and formula for the combined score is highly correlated with the vote score which leads to being voted as an All-Star.

However, there are many other factors which also lead to being voted in as an All-Star which include external influences such as Instagram followers and popularity off the court. For someone such as LeBron James, it'd be a no-brainer he would be voted in every single time considering his amazing consistency and his following with over hundreds of millions of people through social media.

If we could conduct further research, it would be wise to not only understand statistics within basketball but also outside through social media followers considering half of the All-Star vote is dependent on the fans. As players interact more with the fans, this could be a major impact regarding how Instagram followers could also be dependent to measure the vote.

Moreover, different years have different methodologies of voting. For example, before 2017, the All-Star voting criteria was solely based on the fans, and so they took advantage of this and voted for a player, Zaza Pachulia, who definitely was not up to the standards as opposed to the regular All-Star caliber player. Hence, this study could be completely different and maybe more dependent on other factors such as popularity rather than on-court performance as opposed to now where players and media also have a say in who is an All-Star.
